  "prompt": "Why did Buddhism spread in East Asia and not in its native land India?",
  "response": "Buddhism spread extensively in East Asia while declining in India due to several complex historical and social factors:\n\n1. In East Asia:\n- Rulers actively supported Buddhism\n- Missionary activities were successful\n- Buddhism complemented existing philosophical traditions like Confucianism and Taoism\n- Peaceful transmission through trade routes\n- Adaptable philosophical nature\n\n2. In India:\n- Resurgence of Hinduism\n- Brahmin religious leaders' opposition\n- Muslim invasions from 11th-13th centuries\n- Lack of strong institutional support\n- Competition from other religious traditions\n- Absorption of Buddhist ideas into Hinduism\n\n3. Specific decline factors in India:\n- Nalanda University's destruction by Muslim invaders\n- Decreased royal patronage\n- Assimilation of Buddhist concepts into Hinduism\n- Loss of political support\n\n4. East Asian receptiveness:\n- Cultural openness to new philosophical ideas\n- Compatibility with existing belief systems\n- Emphasis on meditation and philosophical contemplation\n- Silk Road trade routes facilitating cultural exchange\n\n5. Institutional differences:\n- East Asian Buddhist institutions were more organized\n- Stronger monastic traditions\n- Better preservation of scriptures and practices\n\nThese multifaceted reasons explain Buddhism's divergent trajectories in India and East Asia.",
